# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: proxy-servers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] In computer networking, a **proxy server** is a intermediary server application between a client requesting a resource and the server then providing that resource.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Instead of connecting directly to a server that can fulfil a request for a resource, such as a file or web page, the client directs the request to the proxy server, which evaluates the request and performs the required network transactions.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] This serves as a method to control the complexity of the request or provide additional benefits such as load balancing, privacy or security.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Proxies were devised to add structure and encapsulation to distributed systems.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A proxy server may reside on the user's **local computer**, or at any point between the user's computer and the destination servers.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A proxy server that passes unmodified requests and responses is usually called a gateway or sometimes a *tunneling proxy*.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A forward proxy is an Internet-facing proxy used to retrieve data from a wide range of sources (in most cases, anywhere on the Internet).
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A reverse proxy is usually an internal-facing proxy used as a front-end to control and protect access to a server on a private network.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A reverse proxy commonly also performs tasks such as load-balancing, authentication, decryption, and caching.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] An open proxy is a forwarding proxy server that is accessible by any Internet user.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] In 2008, network security expert Gordon Lyon estimated that "hundreds of thousands" of open proxies are operated on the Internet.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A reverse proxy (or surrogate) is a proxy server that appears to clients to be an ordinary server.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Reverse proxies send requests to one or more ordinary servers that handle the request.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The response from the original server is returned as if it came directly from the proxy server, leaving the client with no knowledge of the original server.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Reverse proxies are installed in the vicinity of one or more web servers.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] All traffic coming from the Internet and with a destination of one of the neighborhood's web servers goes through the proxy server.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The use of "reverse" originates in its counterpart, the "forward" proxy.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The reverse proxy sits closer to the web server and serves only a restricted set of websites.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A forward proxy is a server that routes traffic between clients and another system, which is, in most cases, external to the network.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] This means it can regulate traffic according to preset policies, convert and mask client IP addresses, enforce security protocols, and block unknown traffic.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A forward proxy enhances security and policy enforcement within an internal network.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A reverse proxy, instead of protecting the client, is used to protect the servers.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A reverse proxy accepts a request from a client, forwards that request to another one of many other servers, and then returns the results from the server that specifically processed the request to the client.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Effectively, a reverse proxy acts as a gateway between clients, users, and application servers and handles all the traffic routing whilst also protecting the identity of the server that physically processes the request.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A content-filtering web proxy server provides administrative control over the content that may be relayed in one or both directions through the proxy.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] It is commonly used in both commercial and non-commercial organizations (especially schools) to ensure that Internet usage conforms to acceptable use policy.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Content filtering proxy servers will often support user authentication to control web access.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] It also usually produces logs, either to give detailed information about the URLs accessed by specific users or to monitor bandwidth usage statistics.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] It may also communicate to daemon-based or ICAP-based antivirus software to provide security against viruses and other malware by scanning incoming content in real-time before it enters the network.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Many workplaces, schools, and colleges restrict websites and online services that are accessible and available in their buildings.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Governments also censor undesirable content.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] This is done either with a specialized proxy, called a content filter (both commercial and free products are available), or by using a cache-extension protocol such as ICAP, which allows plug-in extensions to an open caching architecture.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Websites commonly used by students to circumvent filters and access blocked content often include a proxy, from which the user can then access the websites that the filter is trying to block.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Requests may be filtered by several methods, such as a URL or DNS blacklists, URL regex filtering, MIME filtering, or content keyword filtering.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Blacklists are often provided and maintained by web-filtering companies, often grouped into categories (pornography, gambling, shopping, social networks, etc.).
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The proxy then fetches the content, assuming the requested URL is acceptable.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] At this point, a dynamic filter may be applied on the return path.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] For example, JPEG files could be blocked based on fleshtone matches, or language filters could dynamically detect unwanted language.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] If the content is rejected, then an HTTP fetch error may be returned to the requester.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Most web filtering companies use an internet-wide crawling robot that assesses the likelihood that content is a certain type.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Manual labor is used to correct the resultant database based on complaints or known flaws in the content-matching algorithms.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Some proxies scan outbound content, e.g., for data loss prevention, or scan content for malicious software.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Web filtering proxies are not able to peer inside secure sockets HTTP transactions, assuming the chain-of-trust of SSL/TLS (Transport Layer Security) has not been tampered with.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The SSL/TLS chain-of-trust relies on trusted root certificate authorities.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] In a workplace setting where the client is managed by the organization, devices may be configured to trust a root certificate whose private key is known to the proxy.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] In such situations, proxy analysis of the contents of an SSL/TLS transaction becomes possible.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The proxy is effectively operating a man-in-the-middle attack, allowed by the client's trust of a root certificate that the proxy owns.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] If the destination server filters content based on the origin of the request, the use of a proxy can circumvent this filter.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] For example, a server using IP-based geolocation to restrict its service to a certain country can be accessed using a proxy located in that country to access the service.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Web proxies are the most common means of bypassing government censorship, although no more than 3% of Internet users use any circumvention tools.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Some proxy service providers allow businesses access to their proxy network for rerouting traffic for business intelligence purposes.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] In some cases, users can circumvent proxies that filter using blacklists by using services designed to proxy information from a non-blacklisted location.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Proxies can be installed to eavesdrop upon the data-flow between client machines and the web.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] All content sent or accessed, including passwords submitted and cookies used, can be captured and analyzed by the proxy operator.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] For this reason, passwords to online services (such as webmail and banking) should always be exchanged over a cryptographically secured connection, such as SSL.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] By chaining the proxies that do not reveal data about the original requester, it is possible to obfuscate activities from the eyes of the user's destination.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] However, more traces will be left on the intermediate hops, which could be used or offered up to trace the user's activities.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] If the policies and administrators of these other proxies are unknown, the user may fall victim to a false sense of security just because those details are out of sight and mind.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] In what is more of an inconvenience than a risk, proxy users may find themselves being blocked from certain websites, as numerous forums and websites block IP addresses from proxies known to have spammed or trolled the site.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Proxy bouncing can be used to maintain privacy.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A **caching proxy** server accelerates service requests by retrieving the content saved from a previous request made by the same client or even other clients.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Caching proxies keep local copies of frequently requested resources, allowing large organizations to significantly reduce their upstream bandwidth usage and costs, while significantly increasing performance.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Most ISPs and large businesses have a caching proxy.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Caching proxies were the first kind of proxy server.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Web proxies are commonly used to cache web pages from a web server.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Poorly implemented caching proxies can cause problems, such as an inability to use user authentication.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A proxy that is designed to mitigate specific link-related issues or degradation is a Performance Enhancing Proxy (PEPs).
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] These are typically used to improve TCP performance in the presence of high round-trip times or high packet loss (such as wireless or mobile phone networks); or highly asymmetric links featuring very different upload and download rates.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] PEPs can make more efficient use of the network, for example, by merging TCP ACKs (acknowledgements) or compressing data sent at the application layer.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A translation proxy is a proxy server that is used to localize a website experience for different markets.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Traffic from the global audience is routed through the translation proxy to the source website.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] As visitors browse the proxied site, requests go back to the source site where pages are rendered.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The original language content in the response is replaced by the translated content as it passes back through the proxy.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The translations used in a translation proxy can be either machine translation, human translation, or a combination of machine and human translation.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Different translation proxy implementations have different capabilities.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Some allow further customization of the source site for the local audiences, such as excluding the source content or substituting the source content with the original local content.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] An anonymous proxy server (sometimes called a web proxy) generally attempts to anonymize web surfing.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Anonymizers may be differentiated into several varieties.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The destination server (the server that ultimately satisfies the web request) receives requests from the anonymizing proxy server and thus does not receive information about the end user's address.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The requests are not anonymous to the anonymizing proxy server, however, and so a degree of trust is present between the proxy server and the user.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Many proxy servers are funded through a continuous advertising link to the user.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Advertisers use proxy servers for validating, checking, and quality assuring geotargeted ads.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A geotargeting ad server checks the request source IP address and uses a geo-IP database to determine the geographic source of requests.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Using a proxy server that is physically located inside a specific country or a city gives advertisers the ability to test geotargeted ads.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A proxy can keep the internal network structure of a company secret by using network address translation, which can help the security of the internal network.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] This makes requests from machines and users on the local network anonymous.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Proxies can also be combined with firewalls.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] An incorrectly configured proxy can provide access to a network otherwise isolated from the Internet.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Proxies allow websites to make web requests to externally hosted resources (e.g., images, music files, etc.) when cross-domain restrictions prohibit the website from linking directly to the outside domains.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Proxies also allow the browser to make web requests to externally hosted content on behalf of a website when cross-domain restrictions (in place to protect websites from the likes of data theft) prohibit the browser from directly accessing the outside domains.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Secondary market brokers use web proxy servers to circumvent restrictions on online purchases of limited products such as limited sneakers or tickets.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The request from the client is the same as a regular HTTP request except the full URL is passed, instead of just the path.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] This request is sent to the proxy server, the proxy makes the request specified, and returns the response.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Some web proxies allow the HTTP CONNECT method to set up forwarding of arbitrary data through the connection; a common policy is to only forward port 443 to allow HTTPS traffic.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Examples of web proxy servers include Apache (with mod_proxy or Traffic Server), HAProxy, IIS configured as proxy (e.g., with Application Request Routing), Nginx, Privoxy, Squid, Varnish (reverse proxy only), WinGate, Ziproxy, Tinyproxy, RabbIT and Polipo.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] For clients, the problem of complex or multiple proxy-servers is solved by a client-server Proxy auto-config protocol (*PAC file*).
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Various operating systems (such as Windows, Android, macOS, iOS, Xbox OS and PlayStation OS) and various browsers (such as Edge, Chrome, Safari and Firefox) can support Web proxy.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] SOCKS also forwards arbitrary data after a connection phase, and is similar to HTTP CONNECT in web proxies.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] An **intercepting proxy** redirects or filters client traffic without being explicitly selected by the client.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] It is therefore often deployed without requiring browser or application proxy settings, and clients may be unaware that their traffic is passing through a proxy.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] In HTTP terminology, an interception proxy differs from a conventional HTTP proxy because it is not chosen by the user agent; instead, it is placed in the network path and filters or redirects outgoing traffic, commonly TCP port 80 traffic.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] TCP Intercept is a traffic filtering security feature that protects TCP servers from TCP SYN flood attacks, which are a type of denial-of-service attack.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] TCP Intercept is available for IP traffic only.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] In 2009 a security flaw in the way that transparent proxies operate was published by Robert Auger, and the Computer Emergency Response Team issued an advisory listing dozens of affected transparent and intercepting proxy servers.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Intercepting proxies are commonly used in businesses to enforce acceptable use policies and to ease administrative overheads since no client browser configuration is required.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] This second reason, however, is mitigated by features such as Active Directory group policy, or DHCP and automatic proxy detection.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Intercepting proxies are also commonly used by ISPs in some countries to save upstream bandwidth and improve customer response times by caching.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] This is more common in countries where bandwidth is more limited (e.g, island nations) or must be paid for.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The diversion or interception of a TCP connection creates several issues.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] First, the original destination IP and port must somehow be communicated to the proxy.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] This is not always possible (e.g., where the gateway and proxy reside on different hosts).
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] There is a class of cross-site attacks that depend on certain behaviors of intercepting proxies that do not check or have access to information about the original (intercepted) destination.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] This problem may be resolved by using an integrated packet-level and application-level appliance or software, which is then able to communicate this information between the packet handler and the proxy.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Intercepting also creates problems for HTTP authentication, especially connection-oriented authentication such as NTLM, as the client browser believes it is talking to a server rather than a proxy.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] This can cause problems where an intercepting proxy requires authentication, and then the user connects to a site that also requires authentication.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Finally, intercepting connections can cause problems for HTTP caches, as some requests and responses become uncacheable by a shared cache.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] In integrated firewall/proxy servers where the router/firewall is on the same host as the proxy, communicating original destination information can be done by any method, for example, Microsoft TMG or WinGate.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Interception can also be performed using Cisco's WCCP (Web Cache Control Protocol).
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] This proprietary protocol resides on the router and is configured from the cache, allowing the cache to determine what ports and traffic are sent to it via transparent redirection from the router.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] This redirection can occur in one of two ways: GRE tunneling (OSI Layer 3) or MAC rewrites (OSI Layer 2).
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Once traffic reaches the proxy machine itself, interception is commonly performed with NAT (Network Address Translation).
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Such setups are invisible to the client browser, but leave the proxy visible to the web server and other devices on the internet side of the proxy.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Recent Linux and some BSD releases provide TPROXY (transparent proxy), which performs IP-level (OSI Layer 3) transparent interception and spoofing of outbound traffic, hiding the proxy IP address from other network devices.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A CGI web proxy accepts target URLs using a Web form in the user's browser window, processes the request, and returns the results to the user's browser.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Consequently, it can be used on a device or network that does not allow "true" proxy settings to be changed.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The first recorded CGI proxy, named "rover" at the time but renamed in 1998 to "CGIProxy", was developed by American computer scientist James Marshall in early 1996 for an article in "Unix Review" by Rich Morin.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The majority of CGI proxies are powered by one of CGIProxy (written in the Perl language), Glype (written in the PHP language), or PHProxy (written in the PHP language).
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] As of April 2016, CGIProxy has received about two million downloads, Glype has received more than half a million downloads, whilst PHProxy still receives hundreds of downloads per week.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Despite waning in popularity due to VPNs and other privacy methods, as of September 2021 there are still a few hundred CGI proxies online.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Some CGI proxies were set up for purposes such as making websites more accessible to disabled people, but have since been shut down due to excessive traffic, usually caused by a third party advertising the service as a means to bypass local filtering.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Since many of these users do not care about the collateral damage they are causing, it became necessary for organizations to hide their proxies, disclosing the URLs only to those who take the trouble to contact the organization and demonstrate a genuine need.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A suffix proxy allows a user to access web content by appending the name of the proxy server to the URL of the requested content (e.g., "en.wikipedia.org.*SuffixProxy.com*").
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Suffix proxy servers are easier to use than regular proxy servers, but they do not offer high levels of anonymity, and their primary use is for bypassing web filters.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] However, this is rarely used due to more advanced web filters.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Tor is a system intended to provide online anonymity.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Tor client software routes Internet traffic through a worldwide volunteer network of servers for concealing a user's computer location or usage from someone conducting network surveillance or traffic analysis.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Using Tor makes tracing Internet activity more difficult, and is intended to protect users' personal freedom and their online privacy.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] This reduces the possibility of the original data being unscrambled or understood in transit.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The I2P anonymous network ('I2P') is a proxy network aiming at online anonymity.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] It implements garlic routing, which is an enhancement of Tor's onion routing.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] I2P is fully distributed and works by encrypting all communications in various layers and relaying them through a network of routers run by volunteers in various locations.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] By keeping the source of the information hidden, I2P offers censorship resistance.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The goals of I2P are to protect users' personal freedom, privacy, and ability to conduct confidential business.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Each user of I2P runs an I2P router on their computer (node).
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The I2P router takes care of finding other peers and building anonymizing tunnels through them.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] I2P provides proxies for all protocols (HTTP, IRC, SOCKS, ...).
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The proxy concept refers to a layer-7 application in the OSI reference model.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Network address translation (NAT) is similar to a proxy but operates in layer 3.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] In the client configuration of layer-3 NAT, configuring the gateway is sufficient.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] However, for the client configuration of a layer-7 proxy, the destination of the packets that the client generates must always be the proxy server (layer 7), then the proxy server reads each packet and finds out the true destination.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Because NAT operates at layer 3, it is less resource-intensive than the layer-7 proxy, but also less flexible.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] As we compare these two technologies, we might encounter a terminology known as 'transparent firewall'.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] **Transparent firewall** means that the proxy uses the layer-7 proxy advantages without the knowledge of the client.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The client presumes that the gateway is a NAT in layer 3, and it does not have any idea about the inside of the packet, but through this method, the layer-3 packets are sent to the layer-7 proxy for investigation.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A DNS proxy server takes DNS queries from a (usually local) network and forwards them to an Internet Domain Name Server.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Some client programs "SOCKS-ify" requests, which allows adaptation of any networked software to connect to external networks via certain types of proxy servers (mostly SOCKS).
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] A residential proxy (RESIP) is an intermediary that uses a real IP address provided by an Internet service provider with physical devices such as mobile phones and end-user computers.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Instead of connecting directly to a server, residential proxy users connect to the target through residential IP addresses.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] The target then identifies them as organic internet users.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] It does not let any tracking tool identify the reallocation of the user.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Any residential proxy can send any number of concurrent requests, and IP addresses are directly related to a specific region.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Unlike regular residential proxies, which hide the user's real IP address behind another IP address, rotating residential proxies, also known as *backconnect proxies*, conceal the user's real IP address behind a pool of proxies.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] These proxies switch between themselves at every session or at regular intervals.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Despite providers' assertions that the proxy hosts are voluntarily participating, numerous proxies are operated on potentially compromised hosts, including Internet of things devices.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] Through the process of cross-referencing the hosts, researchers have identified and analyzed logs that have been classified as potentially unwanted program and exposed a range of unauthorized activities conducted by RESIP hosts.
[src:proxy-servers/proxy-server] These activities encompassed illegal promotion, fast fluxing, phishing, hosting malware, and more.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:proxy-servers/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] The protocol was originally designed and developed by David Koblas, a system administrator of MIPS Computer Systems.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] After MIPS was taken over by Silicon Graphics in 1992, Koblas presented a paper on SOCKS at that year's Usenix Security Symposium, making SOCKS publicly available.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] The protocol was extended to version 4 by Ying-Da Lee of NEC.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] The SOCKS reference architecture and client are owned by Permeo Technologies, a spin-off from NEC.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] The SOCKS5 protocol was originally a security protocol that made firewalls and other security products easier to administer.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] The protocol was developed in collaboration with Aventail Corporation, which markets the technology outside of Asia.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] The circuit/session level nature of SOCKS make it a versatile tool in forwarding any TCP (or UDP since SOCKS5) traffic, creating an interface for all types of routing tools.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] Destination port number, meaningful if granted in BIND, should otherwise be ignored.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] Together with DSTPORT the ip:port the client should bind to.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] From this point onwards, any data sent from the SOCKS client to the SOCKS server is relayed to *66.102.7.99*, and vice versa.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] The command field may be 0x01 for "connect" or 0x02 for "bind"; the "bind" command allows incoming connections for protocols such as active FTP.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] The client should set the first three bytes of DSTIP to NULL and the last byte to a non-zero value.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] (This corresponds to IP address 0.0.0.x, with x nonzero, an inadmissible destination address and thus should never occur if the client can resolve the domain name.) Following the NULL byte terminating USERID, the client must send the destination domain name and terminate it with another NULL byte.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] This is used for both "connect" and "bind" requests.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] A server using protocol SOCKS4a must check the DSTIP in the request packet.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] If it represents address 0.0.0.x with nonzero x, the server must read in the domain name that the client sends in the packet.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] The server should resolve the domain name and make connection to the destination host if it can.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] The SOCKS5 protocol is defined in RFC 1928.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] It is an incompatible extension of the SOCKS4 protocol; it offers more choices for authentication and adds support for IPv6 and UDP, the latter of which can be used for DNS lookups.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] The subsequent authentication is method-dependent.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] After authentication the connection can proceed.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] destination address, see the address structure above.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] Since clients are allowed to use either resolved addresses or domain names, a convention from cURL exists to label the domain name variant of SOCKS5 "socks5h", and the other simply "socks5".
[src:proxy-servers/socks] A similar convention exists between SOCKS4a and SOCKS4.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] Client software must have native SOCKS support in order to connect through SOCKS.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] Socksifiers allow applications to access the networks to use a proxy without needing to support any proxy protocols.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] The most common way is to set up a virtual network adapter and appropriate routing tables to send traffic through the adapter.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] Lack of request and packets exchange encryption makes SOCKS practically vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks and IP addresses eavesdropping, which in consequence clears a way to censorship by governments.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] SOCKS proxies, particularly SOCKS5, generally provide improved performance and broader protocol support compared to SOCKS4, making them suitable for use cases involving high concurrency and UDP traffic.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] Unlike HTTP proxies, SOCKS5 operates at the session layer and does not inspect or filter data, which reduces overhead and can result in lower latency beneficial for latency-sensitive applications such as gaming or streaming.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] Benchmarks of various SOCKS5 implementations show that it can handle thousands of simultaneous connections with response times often within milliseconds, demonstrating high throughput potential under load.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] However, SOCKS lacks built-in encryption, leaving traffic vulnerable to interception and making it less secure than virtual private networks (VPNs) or HTTPS proxies that provide encapsulation and data integrity.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] Additionally, using a SOCKS proxy adds an extra network hop, potentially increasing latency and affecting performance-sensitive scenarios.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] While SOCKS5 supports UDP through the `UDP ASSOCIATE` command, the use of UDP proxying complicates firewall traversal and may be unreliable in some network environments.
[src:proxy-servers/socks] These characteristics determine the practical performance capabilities and limitations of SOCKS, defining its appropriate use in many proxying scenarios but limiting its suitability where encryption or minimal latency is required.
